**Code Explanation:**

The code performs a multinomial logistic regression to predict latent class membership (derived in Step 3) using organizational enablers, company culture, affective disposition factors, and demographic controls (job profile, sector, country). 1. Data Preparation: It loads the dummy-encoded dataset and maps the target variable LCA_Class_Name to integers, setting 'Stagnant Neutral' as the reference class (0). 2. Feature Engineering: It identifies the key predictors (QKB_1_11, QKB_1_4, Company_Culture_Index, and the two Affective_Disposition factors) and standardizes them. An interaction term between QKB_1_11 (employee involvement) and QKB_1_4 (regular training) is created. Missing values are imputed with the median to retain the full sample. 3. Multicollinearity Check: Variance Inflation Factors (VIF) are calculated to ensure no severe multicollinearity exists among the predictors. 4. Model Fitting: A multinomial logistic regression (MNLogit from statsmodels) is fitted using the BFGS optimization method (falling back to Newton-Raphson or L-BFGS if needed). 5. Results Extraction: Standardized coefficients, standard errors, z-scores, odds ratios (OR), 95% confidence intervals, and FDR-corrected p-values are extracted and saved to data/mnlogit_results.csv. Key results are printed to the console. 6. Cross-Validation: A 5-fold stratified cross-validation is performed using scikit-learn's LogisticRegression to assess the predictive stability and accuracy of the model. 7. Sensitivity Analysis: The model is re-fitted on a subset of the data excluding respondents who answered 'Not sure' or had missing values in the key organizational predictors. The coefficients are compared to the full model to ensure robustness.

